    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute a global P95 threshold for every distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair using the full available time series for that pair. Then filter metric.csv to only rows within the incident window: 2022-03-20 22:30:00 to 2022-03-20 23:00:00 in UTC+8. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: (1) number of points in the window that have value >= global P95, (2) earliest timestamp of such an anomalous point in the window (if any), (3) maximum value in the window, and (4) the global P95 value. Return a compact table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs ranked by anomaly count (most anomalies first). For each row show: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95. If no anomalies are found with P95, also return the top 20 pairs with the largest single-point relative breach (max_value_in_window / global_p95) sorted descending. Limit output to these aggregated rows only."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step computed global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) and inspected the incident window; the top hits were dominated by static/monotonic KPIs (start times, total disk size, committed virtual memory) which are not actionable. The earliest anomalous timestamp among those hits was ~1647787000 (2022-03-20 22:36:40+08), and error_logs.csv shows 4 error log entries for frontend-1 around 1647786959–1647787021. To find an actual operational fault we must focus on dynamic resource and network KPIs (CPU, memory usage, network packet counts/errors/retransmits, and I/O throughput/latency) and look for consecutive breaches during the 22:30–23:00 window. Next we should re-scan metric.csv but restrict to dynamic KPI name patterns and report compact anomaly aggregates (using the global P95 thresholds already computed per full series).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, select all distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs whose kpi_name includes any of these keywords (case-insensitive): 'cpu', 'memory', 'container_cpu', 'container_memory', 'network', 'transmit', 'receive', 'packet', 'error', 'retransmit', 'retransmission', 'fs_read', 'fs_write', 'read_seconds', 'write_seconds', 'io', 'disk.read', 'disk.write'. For each selected pair: (a) compute the global P95 using the full available series for that pair, (b) filter its points to the incident window 2022-03-20 22:30:00–23:00:00 UTC+8 and count how many points in the window exceed (>=) the global P95, (c) find the earliest timestamp in the window that exceeds the global P95 (if any), and (d) report the max value in the window and the global P95. Return a compact table of the top 20 pairs sorted by anomaly_count (descending). For each row show: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95. If no pair has anomaly_count>0, instead return the top 20 pairs (from the selected set) ranked by the ratio max_value_in_window/global_p95 (descending) with the same columns."
}

{
