    "instruction": "Diagnose metric.csv keyword matches. Using metric.csv, (1) count how many distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs exist where kpi_name (case-insensitive) matches any of these substrings: 'cpu', 'memory', 'mem', 'container_cpu', 'container_memory', 'network', 'transmit', 'receive', 'packet', 'error', 'retransmit', 'retransmission', 'fs', 'read', 'write', 'io', 'disk', 'blk'. (2) For those matching pairs, count how many metric rows fall inside the incident window 2022-03-20 22:30:00–23:00:00 UTC+8. (3) Return a compact list (top 20) of matching kpi_name values with their global total counts (most frequent first) and up to 20 distinct cmdb_id examples for these matching KPIs (with counts). Also return the two timestamp bounds (min and max) observed among matching rows (if any). Limit output to these aggregates only."
}

{
    "analysis": "You diagnosed that a large number of dynamic KPIs (CPU, memory, network, fs, I/O) exist and that many matching rows fall inside the incident window (144,834 rows, 4,684 distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs). The earlier P95 scan returned many static/monotonic metrics (start times, total disk) that are not useful. To locate real faults we must detect consecutive breaches (faults) of dynamic KPIs inside the incident window using global thresholds (P95 computed from the full series for each pair). The next step is to identify which component-KPI pairs show sustained (consecutive) threshold breaches during 22:30–23:00; those sustained runs are candidate faults that can be prioritized for trace/log analysis.",
