    "instruction": "Using metric.csv but restricted to the matching KPI set discovered earlier (the case-insensitive substring matches against dynamic keywords), do the following: For each distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name): (1) compute its global P95 using the full available series for that pair; (2) filter its points to the incident window 2022-03-20 22:30:00–23:00:00 UTC+8 and identify all consecutive runs of one-minute-sampled points where value >= global_P95; (3) for each pair produce these aggregates: total number of breach points in the window (anomaly_count), the length of the longest consecutive breach run (max_run_length), the start timestamp of the longest run (earliest_longest_run_start), the maximum value observed in the window (max_value_in_window), and the global_P95. Return a compact table of the top 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs sorted by max_run_length (desc), then by anomaly_count (desc), showing the five aggregates listed above and limit to top 20 rows only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected dynamic KPIs and found many matches in the incident window, but the top consecutive-breach results were dominated by monotonic/static JVM/runtime metrics (GC counters, compilation totals, start times, total disk size, etc.), which are false positives for transient faults. To proceed we must exclude such monotonic/static KPIs and focus on true usage/rate metrics (CPU usage, memory RSS/usage, network throughput/errors, fs read/write rates, I/O latency). Before computing anomaly runs, we should enumerate which KPI names are truly dynamic (and present in the incident window) so we can restrict the next anomaly scan to that subset.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, select distinct kpi_name values that (case-insensitive) CONTAIN any of these include substrings: 'usage', 'util', 'rss', 'percent', '%', 'cpu', 'memory', 'mem', 'container_cpu', 'container_memory', 'network', 'transmit', 'receive', 'MB', 'bytes', 'packet', 'error', 'errors', 'retransmit', 'retransmission', 'fs_reads', 'fs_writes', 'reads', 'writes', 'read_seconds', 'write_seconds', 'io', 'throughput'. Exclude any kpi_name that (case-insensitive) CONTAINS any of these static/monotonic substrings: 'start_time', 'StartTime', 'LastGcInfo', 'CollectionCount', 'TotalCompilation', 'CommittedVirtualMemory', 'system.disk.total', 'container_start_time', 'limit', 'capacity', 'total', 'max_usage', 'max', 'count', 'uptime'. For each remaining kpi_name, report: total_count across the full file, window_count (number of rows within incident window 2022-03-20 22:30:00–23:00:00 UTC+8), and up to 5 example cmdb_id values with their counts (most frequent first). Return up to top 50 kpi_name rows sorted by window_count desc. Limit output to these aggregates only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We filtered metric KPIs to a dynamic subset and found that node-6 container network, fs, memory and cpu metrics dominate the incident-window data (large window_counts). This suggests a hotspot around node-6 (and some node-5 CPU cfs metrics). Prior P95 scans were polluted by monotonic JVM/runtime counters; we therefore need a focused anomaly scan only on true usage/rate KPIs (network throughput/errors, container CPU/memory usage, fs read/write rates, and CPU throttling) to detect sustained breaches during 2022-03-20 22:30–23:00 UTC+8. If sustained breaches appear on node-level network or I/O KPIs, those are strong candidates for root cause; if breaches are localized to particular pods (many cmdb_id values per KPI), we'll next use traces and logs to pick the most downstream faulty service/pod.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, restrict to kpi_name values (case-insensitive) that include any of these substrings: 'container_network', 'transmit_MB', 'receive_MB', 'transmit_packets', 'receive_packets', 'transmit_errors', 'receive_errors', 'container_memory', 'container_cpu', 'cpu_usage', 'container_cpu_cfs', 'fs_reads', 'fs_writes', 'reads_MB', 'writes_MB', 'read_seconds', 'write_seconds'. Exclude any kpi_name (case-insensitive) that contains: 'start_time', 'LastGcInfo', 'CollectionCount', 'TotalCompilation', 'CommittedVirtualMemory', 'system.disk.total', 'limit', 'capacity', 'total', 'max_usage', 'count', 'uptime'. For each remaining distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name): (1) compute global P95 using the full series for that pair; (2) filter its points to the incident window 2022-03-20 22:30:00–23:00:00 UTC+8 and identify consecutive one-minute runs where value >= global_P95; (3) produce aggregates: anomaly_count (total breach points in the window), max_run_length (length of the longest consecutive breach run), earliest_longest_run_start (start timestamp of that longest run), max_value_in_window, global_p95. Return a compact table of the top 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs sorted by max_run_length desc then anomaly_count desc; show only the five aggregates plus cmdb_id and kpi_name. Limit output to these aggregated rows only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We filtered metrics to actionable dynamic KPIs and excluded many static/monotonic metrics. The metric analysis found heavy activity localized to node-6 container KPIs and many adservice-0 KPIs, but many breaches were artifacts (global_p95 == 0 or monotonic counters). error_logs.csv contains 4 error entries for frontend-1 around 1647786959–1647787021 (~2022-03-20 22:35–22:37 UTC+8), which overlaps the earliest metric breach timestamps (≈1647787000). To localize the root cause we must now analyze traces (to find which service(s) show elevated error_rate or latency during the window and to determine downstream faulty components) before drilling into logs. The next step is a compact trace anomaly scan using global thresholds.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv: for each distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 threshold from the full available series for that pair. Then restrict data to the incident window 2022-03-20 22:30:00–23:00:00 UTC+8 and, for each pair, count how many points in the window have value >= global_P95, find the earliest timestamp in the window that meets this condition (if any), and the maximum value in the window. Return a compact table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs sorted by anomaly_count (desc) then by earliest_anomaly_timestamp (asc). For each row return: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95. If no pairs have anomaly_count>0, instead return the top 20 pairs (from all trace pairs) ranked by the ratio max_value_in_window/global_p95 (desc) with the same columns."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric and trace scans and found the following: (1) metric hits during the incident window concentrate on node-6 container KPIs and many adservice-0 KPIs, but earlier P95-based breach counts were polluted by static/monotonic metrics and many zero global-P95 values, making those breach counts unreliable; (2) trace results likewise show many zero-P95 artifacts; (3) error_logs.csv contains 4 error entries for frontend-1 with timestamps around 1647786959–1647787021 (~2022-03-20 22:35–22:37 UTC+8), which overlaps the earliest anomalous metric timestamps (~1647787000). Therefore to meaningfully localize the root cause we must ignore KPIs with zero global P95 or monotonic semantics and surface component-KPI pairs that show real, non-trivial deviations from their global P95 during 22:30–23:00. These will be the most actionable candidates for trace/log correlation.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, restrict to dynamic KPI names as in the previous filter (network, container_cpu, container_memory, fs reads/writes, etc.) and exclude monotonic/static KPI name patterns previously listed. For each distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) compute the global P95 from the full series. Discard any pairs whose global_p95 == 0. For the remaining pairs, filter points to the incident window 2022-03-20 22:30:00–23:00:00 UTC+8 and compute: (a) max_value_in_window, (b) ratio = max_value_in_window / global_p95, (c) anomaly_count = number of points in the window where value >= global_p95, and (d) earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first timestamp in the window where value >= global_p95, if any). Return a compact table of the top 20 pairs sorted by ratio (desc), showing: cmdb_id, kpi_name, ratio, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95. If no pairs remain after excluding zero-P95, return a short message indicating that and list the top 20 pairs by max_value_in_window (desc) instead."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have iteratively narrowed candidates: metric analysis showed many artifact breaches from static/monotonic KPIs and many dynamic metrics concentrated on node-6 containers; a focused non-zero-P95 scan surfaced short-lived network receive MB spikes across many services (peaked around ~0.3–0.7 MB, with ratios up to ~24x the baseline) with earliest breach timestamps near 1647787000 (~2022-03-20 22:36:40+08). Trace analysis was noisy due to many zero-P95 traces, but traces and metrics both point to frontend-related errors: error_logs.csv contains 4 error entries for frontend-1 around 1647786959–1647787021, overlapping the metric spike time. This suggests a network-related transient affecting multiple services around ~22:36–22:38. To confirm root cause (component and reason) we need direct evidence of packet/errors on the node or containers hosting many pods (e.g., node-6) and corroborating logs/traces from frontend and downstream services. Next we must (a) inspect error_logs details and log.error_count per component during the window, and (b) check network error counters (receive_errors/transmit_errors) on node-5/node-6 containers to see which containers/nodes had elevated network error counts during the window. This will let us decide whether the root cause is a node-level network failure or a pod-level transient.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Run three compact queries:\n1) From error_logs.csv, return all rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, message) that fall inside the incident window 2022-03-20 22:30:00–23:00:00 UTC+8 (limit rows to all matching rows; there are few).\n2) From log.csv, filter to the incident window and group by cmdb_id and log_name; for each group compute: sum_value (sum of 'value'), max_value, and earliest_timestamp_where_value_gt_0 (if any). Return rows where log_name is 'log.error_count' or 'log.row_count', sorted by sum_value desc, limit top 20.\n3) From metric.csv, select kpi_name values that (case-insensitive) contain either 'receive_errors' or 'transmit_errors' or 'network_receive_errors' or 'network_transmit_errors' (include both node-5 and node-6 metrics). For each distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) compute within the incident window: max_value_in_window and count_nonzero_points (number of points with value>0). Return the top 20 pairs sorted by max_value_in_window desc, showing cmdb_id, kpi_name, max_value_in_window, count_nonzero_points, and the earliest timestamp in-window where value>0 (if any).\nReturn only these aggregated tables (do not print full raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have iteratively narrowed candidates using metrics, traces, and logs. Key facts so far:\n- error_logs.csv: 4 error entries from frontend-1 around 1647786959–1647787021 (~2022-03-20 22:35:59–22:37:01 UTC+8).\n- log.csv: large row_count spikes across frontends and many backend services with earliest >0 around 1647787000 (~22:36:40 UTC+8).\n- metric.csv: many artifact breaches from monotonic JVM/runtime KPIs and many zero-P95 cases; after filtering to meaningful dynamic KPIs and excluding zero-P95, we observed brief inbound network MB spikes across many services with earliest breach timestamps clustered near 1647787000 (~22:36:40+08). Network error counters (receive/transmit errors) were zero during the window.\nInterpretation so far: evidence points to a short transient event around ~22:36–22:38 UTC+8 that caused frontend request errors (frontend-1), a burst of request/row_count activity, and short-lived increases in incoming network MB across many services. No network error counters were set, so the cause may be a transient traffic surge or resource exhaustion (CPU/memory/cfs throttling, I/O pressure) on a shared host (node-6 was prominent in metric coverage). To decide whether the root cause is a node-level resource issue or a distributed traffic spike, we must aggregate node-level usage (across containers on each node) for key resource KPIs (CPU, memory, network rx/tx) and compare per-node aggregated series against global thresholds to see which node (if any) shows a sustained, significant breach starting at the earliest problematic time (~1647787000). If a node (e.g., node-6) shows clear, non-artifact breaches starting at ~1647787000, that would localize the root cause to that node and provide the occurrence time and reason (e.g., node CPU spike or network throughput spike).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Aggregate node-level KPI time series and test for anomalies. Using metric.csv, for each node in {node-1,node-2,node-3,node-4,node-5,node-6} and for each KPI suffix in this list: ['container_cpu_usage_seconds', 'container_memory_rss', 'container_network_receive_MB', 'container_network_transmit_MB'] do the following: (1) build a node-level per-minute time series by summing values at each timestamp across all metric rows whose kpi_name contains the pattern 'container.<node>.<suffix>' (case-sensitive match on 'container.node-X' as appears in kpi_name); (2) compute the global P95 for that aggregated node-KPI time series using the full available series; (3) restrict the aggregated series to the incident window 2022-03-20 22:30:00–23:00:00 UTC+8 and compute: anomaly_count (number of minutes with value >= global_P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first timestamp in window where value >= global_P95, if any), max_value_in_window, and global_p95. Return a compact table of all node-KPI pairs (up to 24 rows) with columns: node (e.g., node-6), kpi_suffix, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95, sorted by anomaly_count desc then max_value_in_window desc. Limit output to this aggregated table only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated node-level KPIs and correlated metrics, traces, and logs. Key findings: (1) error_logs.csv shows frontend-1 emitted 4 error entries around 1647786959–1647787021 (~2022-03-20 22:35:59–22:37:01 UTC+8); (2) many services show log.row_count spikes with earliest >0 at 1647787000 (~22:36:40); (3) per-container analyses revealed brief inbound network MB spikes across many services (some with large ratio vs baseline) with earliest breaches clustered near 1647787000; (4) node-level aggregation shows node-6 had short breaches on container_network_transmit_MB with earliest breach at 1647787000 and also elevated aggregated CPU-seconds around the window. Network error counters remained zero, suggesting no packet error counts were triggered. Synthesis: a short traffic surge or burst around ~1647787000 (~2022-03-20 22:36:40+08) impacted frontends (frontend-1 errors) and caused network/CPU/row_count spikes across many pods; node-6 is a prime candidate since many anomalous KPIs are container.node-6.* and node-6 aggregated network transmit and CPU showed breaches with earliest anomaly at 1647787000. This is not yet definitive—next we must identify which pods on node-6 experienced the largest network receive/transmit spikes at the earliest anomaly timestamp to pinpoint the root cause pod(s) or confirm node-level origin.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, filter rows with timestamp == 1647787000 and where kpi_name contains either 'container.node-6.container_network_receive_MB' or 'container.node-6.container_network_transmit_MB' (case-sensitive substring match as in file). Return the top 20 rows sorted by value (desc). For each row show: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value. Limit output to these rows only."
}

